movesets.name: Offensive Support

items.name: Berry Juice
items.description: Restores 20 HP when at 50% HP or less. One-time use.

items.name: Eviolite
items.description: Boosts Defense and Special Defense of holder by 50% if it is an NFE Pokemon.

movesets.description:
Moves

This set has the same basic offensive functions, but has even greater bulk and also serves as a reliable supporter for its team. Play Rough and Earthquake provide near-perfect attacking coverage for Snubbull, and Heal Bell is used to keep both Snubbull and its team free of annoying status afflictions that can limit their potential. Thunder Wave is used to cripple foes and put them at a Speed disadvantage.

Set Details

When Eviolite is taken into account, a Careful nature and the given EVs give Snubbull an incredibly bulky defensive spread of 24 / 21 / 21. Intimidate further helps Snubbull take hits on the physical side. No Attack investment is required for this set, as support Snubbull prefers additional bulk, and it still hits hard uninvested with its trademark near-perfect coverage. This set also has no Speed investment, but with Thunder Wave as one of its disruptive options, Snubbull will be outspeeding most of its switch-ins regardless.

Usage Tips

With the huge array of Fighting- and Dark-type attacks flying around the tier, it is beyond easy to find an opportunity to bring Snubbull in to clear status for its team or spread paralysis on the opponent's team. After the opposing team is weakened, when there is less nead for Heal Bell or Thunder Wave, Snubbull can often find opportunities to take advantage of its excellent attacking coverage, including hitting notable threats such as Mienfoo, Tyrunt, Scraggy, and Vulpix for super effective damage.

Team Options

Eviolite Mienfoo with U-turn is an incredible teammate to get Snubbull in safely, and also threatens Pawniard and other Steel-types that give Snubbull a hard time after it knocks out a foe. Ground-types such as Drilbur make for excellent partners since they directly threaten the Steel- and Poison-types that can hurt Snubbull with their STABs. Abra easily gets rid of Koffing if it's an issue. Ferroseed forms an incredible defensive core with Snubbull, with both of them covering each other's weaknesses and both dishing out crippling moves. Anything that appreciates paralysis support is happy to have Snubbull on its team; slower Pokemon such as Timburr as Munchlax really appreciate the Speed advantage.

movesets.name: Snubbull Trouble

items.name: Berry Juice
items.description: Restores 20 HP when at 50% HP or less. One-time use.

items.name: Eviolite
items.description: Boosts Defense and Special Defense of holder by 50% if it is an NFE Pokemon.

movesets.description:
Moves

Play Rough is the obligatory hard-hitting physical STAB attack, smacking most of the tier at least neutrally, and has the additional chance of lowering the target's Attack stat. Earthquake hits the Fire-, Steel-, and Poison-types that resist Fairy-type attacks for super effective damage, and therefore provides perfect coverage, with very few exceptions. Close Combat is a very powerful Fighting-type option that hits many Pokemon for super effective damage, but Crunch can be used to take a huge bite out of Gastly and Bronzor, two Pokemon that wall Fairy + Ground coverage via the Levitate ability. Crunch also lets Snubbull have an easier time against Slowpoke, a notable physical wall. With its sheer power, access to the Intimidate ability to neuter opposing physical attackers, and access to high-powered attacks, Snubbull forces a lot of switches, and thus has opportunities to spread status with Thunder Wave, making its enemies even easier to break down. Alternatively, Snubbull can utilize Bulk Up to become a physical juggernaut while taking advantage of the free turn provided by a fleeing foe.

Set Details

The given EV spread with Intimidate as the ability and Eviolite as the held item allow Snubbull to tank hits from both physical and special attackers, while still maintaining a formidable offensive presence. An Adamant nature is the optimal choice for achieving the highest immediate power possible, and Snubbull doesn't need much Speed, as it can take a lot of hits and is slower than most things even with a Jolly nature or heavy Speed investment. However, because it only takes 36 EVs to raise its Speed by a stat point, Snubbull does invest a little, so that it can outspeed certain slower Pokemon such as Bronzor and Spritzee. Berry Juice is an option over Eviolite, as it is Snubbull's only way to restore lost health, and can help Snubbull maintain momentum if it mistakenly switches into a painful super effective attack. Berry Juice is always the preferred item if Bulk Up is used over Thunder Wave, as Snubbull is otherwise unable to recover health after setting up.

Usage Tips

Most Fighting-, Dark-, and Dragon-types stand absolutely no chance against Snubbull. Scraggy is particularly vulnerable as it has a 4x weakness to Fairy-type moves. Intimidate turns Snubbull into a huge physical tank that can check other physically inclined Pokemon without even having a type advantage against them. Snubbull must wary of Poison- and Steel-type attacks, especially on the special side, as it cannot take those very well. Defiant Pawniard walks all over Snubbull if Intimidate activates its Defiant ability, as Pawniard easily outspeeds and a +1 Iron Head from it is a clean OHKO on Snubbull, regardless of the item chosen; thankfully, switching into Snubbull is a huge risk for Pawniard and Intimidate doesn't activate in this scenario.

Team Options

Lickitung with Wish and Toxic is an invaluable partner for Snubbull, as Snubbull can cover Lickitung's sole weakness to Fighting-type attacks and Lickitung can soften up Snubbull's enemies as well as keep both itself and Snubbull alive. Pawniard makes for a good teammate as well, as it can take the Poison- and Steel-type attacks aimed at Snubbull with ease, while Snubbull sponges the Fighting-type attacks aimed at Pawniard, forming not only a formidable offensive core but also one that covers all of the important weak points of the two. Inkay is the only Pokemon whose STABs score super effective damage on all three Pokemon in the tier that wall Fairy + Ground coverage: Bronzor, Gastly, and Koffing. Other Pokemon that can cover Snubbull's weaknesses well are Ghost-types such as Honedge, and Frillish, as well as Ground-types such as Hippoppotas and Drilbur. In addition to the aforementioned Pawniard and Honedge, Magnemite is an ideal Steel-type partner, as it is a bulky Pokemon that can trap and deal with the opposing Steel-types that might give Snubbull problems.
